 important decision you'll make is choosing the right location. You may want to set up on a busy street in the city center, at a shopping center, or in a new mall.<\/p>\n","url":"https://www.notzarla.com/guides/how-to-open-a-pizza-shop#how-to-open-a-pizza-shop-section8-step1","image":{"@type":"ImageObject","url":"https://www.notzarla.com/images/zarla-find-a-supplier-in-your-area-288x288-20200623.png?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2","height":"288","width":"288"}},{"@type":"HowToStep","position":"2","name":"<p>Transform the location.<\/p>\n","text":"<p>Once you have your location, it's time to make the pizza spot of your dreams. If your budget allows it, you could do some renovations and use the opportunity to set your pizza place apart from the competition.<\/p>\n","url":"https://www.notzarla.com/guides/how-to-open-a-pizza-shop#how-to-open-a-pizza-shop-section8-step2","image":{"@type":"ImageObject","url":"https://www.notzarla.com/images/zarla-transform-the-location-288x288-20200817.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2","height":"288","width":"288"}},{"@type":"HowToStep","position":"3","name":"<p>Think about the branding of your pizza shop.<\/p>\n","text":"<p>What do you want to say about your place? Choosing a brand for your pizza business could depend on your service style. All the elements, from lighting and seating to flooring, need to align under one theme.<\/p>\n","url":"https://www.notzarla.com/guides/how-to-open-a-pizza-shop#how-to-open-a-pizza-shop-section8-step3","image":{"@type":"ImageObject","url":"https://www.notzarla.com/images/zarla-consider-your-brand-288x288-20200703.png?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2","height":"288","width":"288"}},{"@type":"HowToStep","position":"4","name":"<p>Equip your pizza shop.<\/p>\n","text":"<p>Good quality, reliable equipment is essential for running a successful pizza shop. It is important to buy the best equipment your budget will allow as cutting corners on equipment will cost you later.<\/p>\n","url":"https://www.notzarla.com/guides/how-to-open-a-pizza-shop#how-to-open-a-pizza-shop-section8-step4","image":{"@type":"ImageObject","url":"https://www.notzarla.com/images/zarla-equip-your-pizza-shop-288x288-20200817.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2","height":"288","width":"288"},"itemListElement":[{"@type":"HowToTip","text":"<p>Keep in mind that your brand and concept will determine a lot of the equipment you invest in. For example, if you're a traditionalist pizzeria, you'll need a wood-fired brick pizza oven. If you want an eclectic feel for the restaurant, you'll need interesting artwork and furniture.<\/p>\n"},{"@type":"HowToTip","text":"<p>A pizza oven can cost from $300 to $20,000 and over, dough sheeters cost from $1,500 to $10,000, refrigerators and freezers can cost from $3,000 to over $10,000, and preparation supplies (pizza cutters, cutting boards, serving utensils, pizza boxes, etc.) can cost anywhere from $200 to over $2,000.<\/p>\n"}]},{"@type":"HowToStep","position":"5","name":"<p>Make sure your kitchen layout works.<\/p>\n","text":"<p>The kitchen is the heart of your restaurant, so the layout is essential. It needs to adhere to safety regulations and it must be easy to work in. Ask your kitchen management staff to help you make design decisions.<\/p>\n","url":"https://www.notzarla.com/guides/how-to-open-a-pizza-shop#how-to-open-a-pizza-shop-section8-step5","image":{"@type":"ImageObject","url":"https://www.notzarla.com/images/zarla-make-sure-your-kitchen-layout-works-288x288-20200817.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2","height":"288","width":"288"}}]},{"@type":"HowToSection","position":"9","name":"<p>Hire employees.<\/p>\n","itemListElement":[{"@type":"HowToStep","position":"1","name":"<p>List how many employees you will need in your pizza shop.<\/p>\n","text":"<p>Regardless of the size of your pizzeria, there are a number of roles that need filling if your business is to be successful. In the beginning, there will be an overlap of duties while your business grows, but in time you will need to employ people to fill specific roles.<\/p>\n","url":"https://www.notzarla.com/guides/how-to-open-a-pizza-shop#how-to-open-a-pizza-shop-section9-step1","image":{"@type":"ImageObject","url":"https://www.notzarla.com/images/zarla-decide-if-you-need-to-hire-additional-employees-288x288-20200723.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2","height":"288","width":"288"},"itemListElement":[{"@type":"HowToTip","text":"<p>There are hiring tools, such as Betterteam, to help you with attracting, onboarding, and keeping track of applicants.<\/p>\n"},{"@type":"HowToDirection","text":"<p>A manager will be required to handle purchasing, track inventory, train and manage both front-of-house and kitchen staff, and do marketing. Managers at restaurants are paid an average of $42,387 a year.<\/p>\n"},{"@type":"HowToDirection","text":"<p>A pizza chef will be needed if you want to be experimental with your pizza offerings and make signature pies that will set your pizza shop apart from others. Expect to pay your chef roughly $48,000 a year.<\/p>\n"},{"@type":"HowToDirection","text":"<p>Cooks assist the chef, doing simple preparation while the restaurant is quiet or before the restaurant opens. Cooks are paid an average of $575 to $650 a week.<\/p>\n"},{"@type":"HowToDirection","text":"<p>If you open a dine-in pizza shop, you should consider a bartender to serve your customers drinks. They also prepare the bar, order supplies, check the liquor requisition sheet and inventory, and then clean up the bar area just before closing. A bartender is paid an average of $16 an hour, tips included.<\/p>\n"},{"@type":"HowToDirection","text":"<p>Good servers make a good impression and keep customers coming back. They must be able to handle pressure, multi-task, serve several tables at a time, be friendly, and maintain a positive attitude. Generally, servers are paid minimum wage plus tips.<\/p>\n"},{"@type":"HowToDirection","text":"<p>Dishwashers ensure there are always clean dishes and cutlery available. They are usually paid minimum wage.<\/p>\n"},{"@type":"HowToDirection","text":"<p>You'll need someone to clean the tables, floors, kitchen, and toilets before and after service. In many cases, cleaning staff work for minimum wage.<\/p>\n"},{"@type":"HowToDirection","text":"<p>As your pizza restaurant grows, you might want to employ someone part-time to greet guests, seat them, take reservations, and work the cash register. Hosts are paid minimum wage, mostly.<\/p>\n"}]},{"@type":"HowToStep","position":"2","name":"<p>Have contracts written up.<\/p>\n","text":"<p>Your pizzeria will need a set of basic employment contracts. You can have a lawyer put one together.<\/p>\n","url":"https://www.notzarla.com/guides/how-to-open-a-pizza-shop#how-to-open-a-pizza-shop-section9-step2","image":{"@type":"ImageObject","url":"https://www.notzarla.com/images/zarla-have-contracts-written-up-288x288-20200817.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2","height":"288","width":"288"}}]},{"@type":"HowToSection","position":"10","name":"<p>Market your pizza shop.<\/p>\n","itemListElement":[{"@type":"HowToStep","position":"1","name":"<p>Create a website.<\/p>\n","text":"<p>Your website should be user-friendly, informative, and perfectly aligned with your brand. There are many website builders to choose from and most of them have free versions with lots of templates to help you get started. Make sure you include online ordering and booking for customers.<\/p>\n","url":"https://www.notzarla.com/guides/how-to-open-a-pizza-shop#how-to-open-a-pizza-shop-section10-step1","image":{"@type":"ImageObject","url":"https://www.notzarla.com/images/zarla-build-a-website-288x288-20200817.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2","height":"288","width":"288"},"itemListElement":[{"@type":"HowToTip","text":"<p>Pay-per-click advertising and optimizing your website for search can also have huge payoffs. Do extensive research on these topics or hire a local agency to help you.<\/p>\n"}]},{"@type":"HowToStep","position":"2","name":"<p>Invest in social media.<\/p>\n","text":"<p>Facebook and Instagram lend themselves nicely to pizza shops. Just remember that the point of social media is to actively participate in it. Be accessible to your customers and share relevant pictures, videos, and memes regularly and freely.<\/p>\n","url":"https://www.notzarla.com/guides/how-to-open-a-pizza-shop#how-to-open-a-pizza-shop-section10-step2","image":{"@type":"ImageObject","url":"https://www.notzarla.com/images/zarla-use-social-media-288x288-2020071.png?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2","height":"288","width":"288"}},{"@type":"HowToStep","position":"3","name":"<p>Use the space in your pizza shop.<\/p>\n","text":"<p>Consider using digital signage. You might want to have one or two screens put up in your pizzeria, and instead of having them on a TV channel, use them to advertise, or display menus and items on the menu, promotional deals, or other information. You can design your own digital signage with free digital signage software.<\/p>\n","url":"https://www.notzarla.com/guides/how-to-open-a-pizza-shop#how-to-open-a-pizza-shop-section10-step3","image":{"@type":"ImageObject","url":"https://www.notzarla.com/images/zarla-use-your-space-288x288-20200817.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2","height":"288","width":"288"}},{"@type":"HowToStep","position":"4","name":"<p>Register on Google My Business.<\/p>\n","text":"<p>If you want to appear when someone asks \"where is the nearest pizza shop?\" be sure to register for Google My Business. Also, consider setting up a Yelp page and asking happy customers to rate your business.<\/p>\n","url":"https://www.notzarla.com/guides/how-to-open-a-pizza-shop#how-to-open-a-pizza-shop-section10-step4","image":{"@type":"ImageObject","url":"https://www.notzarla.com/images/zarla-sign-up-for-google-my-business-288x288-20200812.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2","height":"288","width":"288"}}]}]}</script> <div
